Extracting Information from Blood Cells¶

Goal¶

  • Our purpose in this project is extract key information from Blood Cells that can then be utilizied to construct predictive models using state of the art differential geometry machine learning. These modules think in terms of shape, size, and color instead of 1 and 0s
  • We want to extract the shape of the nucleus, shape of the membrane, and color of membrane. These are key markers that medical proffessionals use to determine the type of cell we are looking at
  • We also want to run a CNN for predicting cell type and talk about its potential downsides

Why it matters¶

  • These models can help aid humans in blood differential tests
  • A blood differential test involves counting the number of various types of white blood cells and comparing them to other types, which ensure various treatments are having desired effects.
  • It is also a step in diagnosing 'an infection, anemia, or leukemia'.
  • Neutrophils, for example, are the most common composing 40-60% of all white blood cells .
  • In order to perform this test a blood sample is taken, stained, and cells are then counted, typically by a person, This process could be greatly expedited by removing the need for a human to count the cells.

The Data¶

The dataset consists of roughly 17000 .jpgs of size 360 $\times$ 363. Each image is of a healthy cell not undergoing any sort of treatment. There are 8 types: neutrophils, eosinophils, basophils, lymphocytes, monocytes, immature granulocytes, erythroblasts, and platelets (which are not included in our analysis as opening the file results in a crash).

Erythroblast

Neutrophil

Monocyte

As our dataset is number of images we had to find a way to represent the shape of interest within the image. In order to do this we use scikit image to find contours along the edges of each cell. This output an array of booleans at each pixel, to this we applied a search algorithm which output the path coordinates of the curve contained in this array.

Some of the disadvantages of CNNs and why we should use Geometric Machine Learning Models:

  • They don't encode position and orientation well
  • Needs a lot of data for training
  • Recognize the image as clusters of pixels which are arranged in distinct patterns. They don’t understand them as components of the image.

Issues with most medical cell data:

  • The cells caputered in the images can be in different parts of the image
  • It is hard to get a lot of cell data (our dataset is one of the exceptions)
  • Classification of cells was done based off of sight. Humans are good at reconizing shapes and relationships between shapes. Not relationships between pixels

How Geometric Machine Learning resolves some of these issues:

  • We are just extracting shape of nucleus. Position is irrelavent to us
  • Based off of the results we do not need much data at all to have a classification system
  • Treats images of cells like humans would. Looks at shape of nucleus and difference between shape of nucleus for each class
